                         =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=
                         = "For Birders Only" Echo =
                         =-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=

     I am pleased to announce the availability of a new echo-mail
     conference group for bird watchers named "For Birders Only"!

     This echo will be supported by the Charleston Natural History
     Society (local Audubon chapter) and also expects to get regular
     input from the Cornell University Laboratory of Ornithology and
     "Wild Bird" magazine, as well as rare bird sighting information
     from various sources available through the nationwide rare bird
     hotline, Carolina Bird Club and the South Carolina Wildlife and
     Marine Resources department in Columbia to get us started.  I
     hope that interest will be sufficient in the near future for us
     to bring the headquarters of the National Audubon Society online
     as they have expressed interest to me in hopes of creating a new
     bulletin board to carry similar information!

     This conference group has been active for quite a while, and all
     previous information posted will be available if you want to get
     "up-to-date".  Note that I expect at least two other sources to
     be available shortly - one through Tom Hendricks (13/33) on his
     "Avi-Tech" board which specialized in pet birds (and has another
     echo named 'AVICULTURE' available to pet bird lovers).

     Interested SysOps should contact me via netmail at 372/888 and I
     will arrange for a feed either from my board, or from someone in
     a closer location if possible.

     The "For Birders Only" conference group is mentioned in the next
     (not out as of this writing - August) issue of "Wild Bird"
     magazine on pages 6 and 7 in the 'Bulletin Bird' section.  I will
     post a listing of other boards participating in an upcoming issue
     of "Wild Bird" as well.

     I know there is a lot of interest out there, so let's get started
     and provide a useful vehicle for information to the bird-lovers
     around the country!

     Conference host and SIG-Op will be the real expert in the family:
     Donna Ratledge.

